snippet: The resignation of Prime Minister Ali Larayedh was part of a carefully calibrated plan to end months of gridlock and prepare for new elections in the birthplace of the Arab Spring.
abstract: Ali Larayedh, Tunisia's Islamist prime minister, resigns, ending his party's two-year rule; Larayedh's resignation is setback for Islamists who wanted to lead party into elections, but is part of political agreement with opposition parties to break months of deadlock.
lead_paragraph: The resignation of Prime Minister Ali Larayedh was part of a carefully calibrated plan to end months of gridlock and prepare for new elections in the birthplace of the Arab Spring.

headline.main: Tunisia’s Premier Resigns, Formally Ending His Party’s Rule
